        thermals: {
          id: 'thermals',
          title: 'How Do You Handle Thermal Throttling on a Laptop?',
          content: [
            '**Thermal throttling occurs when the CPU or GPU reaches its temperature limit and reduces clock speed to cool down.** For local LLM inference, this typically kicks in after 10вҖ“15 minutes of sustained generation, reducing speed by 20вҖ“40%.',
          ],
          items: [
            '**Use a laptop stand with airflow clearance** вҖ” raising the laptop 2вҖ“3 cm improves exhaust airflow and reduces throttling onset from 10 to 20+ minutes.',
            '**Disable Intel Turbo Boost / AMD Precision Boost** вҖ” running at base clock speed produces steady performance without thermal spikes. On macOS, install `cpufreq` or use the "Low Power" mode in Battery settings.',
            '**Limit generation batch size** вҖ” avoid regenerating very long responses. Break long tasks into shorter prompts.',
            '**Use Q4_K_M over Q8_0** вҖ” lower quantization requires less computation per token, producing less heat at the cost of marginal quality.',
          ],
          image: '/images/laptop-stand-airflow.svg',
          imageCaption: 'Raising a laptop 2вҖ“3 cm on a stand improves exhaust airflow and delays throttling onset from 10 to 20+ minutes.',
        },
